Brno developers claim that they did not think about the brand famous in the past by mobile phones when creating the warehouse program. The designation Lokia according to CCV is based on the Latin name for one type of dragonfly, the rapid movement of which is to be an analogy to the movement of warehouse workers around the warehouse.
"On the Czech market, the possibility of submissiveness is unlikely. We sell modern cloud software, through which companies equip their warehouse operations, and we are not really aiming for the field of mobile phone production. And we don't want to be compared to a brand that may be running out of train in its field," CCV manager Tomáš Kormaňák told E15.
CCV applied for brand protection in August before the programme was launched by the Industrial Property Office. "It requested protection for products and services belonging to Classes 9, 35 and 42, as the software belongs to Class 9, the related business management services in the warehouse belong to Class 35 and the development of computer software belongs to Class 42 according to the international classification," said Ondrášek.
Nokia's objection is based on the fact that nokia's earlier trade mark is valid in all classes of goods and services and thus covers the widest possible range of goods and services and therefore, of course, also overlaps in classes 9, 35 and 42. 'CCV does not challenge the claim of the objector as regards conformity with those classes of goods and services. In reality, however, these are completely different brands aimed at other target groups," said Ondrášek.
