Bloomberg: Venezuela has bitcoin hidden and doesn't know what to do with them
Venezuela's central bank is conducting internal tests to see if it can hold cryptocurrencies. This is in response to an instruction from the state-owned Petróleos de Venezuela (PDVSA), which seeks to send bitcoins and ethers to the central bank and then to pay the oil firm's suppliers with cryptocurrencies. Employees are also studying the proposal that the central bank could count cryptocurrencies in foreign exchange reserves, which are now close to their 30-year low, Bloomberg reported, citing four sources.
The sanctions imposed by the United States against President Nicolás Maduro's authoritarian regime have largely cut Venezuela off from the global financial system. This has exacerbated the country's economic crisis. At the same time, the current crisis is one of the most serious in the world, forcing officials to use a mixture of different ways of moving money. While Maduro's efforts to launch the world's first state-owned cryptocurrency have failed, continued efforts to use digital currencies show how desperately the government is trying to find ways to circumvent restrictions.
Neither the Central Bank of Venezuela nor PDVSA responded to a request for comment.
It is not clear how PDVSA came to own Bitcoin and ethers, nor how much value it owns these currencies. The company is having trouble obtaining payments from customers through conventional channels because large banks are unwilling to do business with entities subject to sanctions. Last month, the company received most of the $700 million ($16.6 billion) payment in Chinese yuan because the parties were unable to find financial institutions to allow the transaction.
PDVSA may not want to sell cryptocurrencies on the open market, as this would require it to register on the stock exchange and submit to due diligence. Instead, it wants the cryptocurrency to be used by the central bank and paid with it to entities to whom PDVSA owes. Oil firm officials believe that the central bank is less exposed to any obstacles that might arise when paying with cryptocurrencies.
Bitcoin and ethers use a decentralized internet ledger known as blockchain to verify and record transactions. In some cases, relatively anonymous transfers are allowed without the need for an intermediary. Few banks engage in digital currencies because of money laundering problems and client information related to them and complicating compliance.
Cryptocurrencies are returning to prom this year after the 2018 debacle, anticipation of their greater acceptance by institutions and Facebook's plan to come up with its own cryptocurrency. They still remain unstable. Bitcoin has fallen nearly 20 percent in the last four days, but has made a profit of about 130 percent since the beginning of the year.
